# Grand Archive Fundamentals: A Complete Beginner's Guide

Welcome to **Grand Archive TCG** — one of the most exciting trading card games to launch in recent years. Whether you're coming from Magic: The Gathering, Flesh and Blood, or picking up a card game for the first time, this guide will walk you through everything you need to know to get started.

---

## What is Grand Archive?

Grand Archive is an anime-inspired trading card game developed by **Weebs of the Shore**. It launched in 2022 and quickly built a passionate community drawn to its:

- Beautiful anime-style artwork
- Deep strategic gameplay
- Strong collector appeal
- Transparent, player-friendly development team

The core premise: you play as a **champion** — a powerful character with a unique ability — and build a deck of memories and actions to defeat your opponent.

---

## Card Anatomy

Understanding what's on each card is your first step. Here are the key zones:

### The Champion Card

Your champion sits in front of you and is always in play. It has:

- **Level** — champions can level up during the game
- **Health** — if this hits zero, you lose
- **Ability** — a unique passive or activated effect

### Action Cards

These make up the bulk of your deck. Each has:

- **Cost** — how much memory you need to play it
- **Power** — how much damage it deals in combat
- **Durability** — for equipment cards, how many hits it can take
- **Effect** — any special text that triggers

### The Memory System

> The memory system is what makes Grand Archive unique. Every card in your hand can be played face-down as a **memory** to generate resources — or played face-up for its effect.

This means **every card in your deck is useful** — nothing is ever a dead draw.

---

## Core Game Phases

A turn in Grand Archive follows these phases:

1. **Prepare Phase** — draw up to your hand size, reset your memories
2. **Main Phase** — play cards, use champion abilities, set memories
3. **Battle Phase** — attack with your champion or allies
4. **End Phase** — discard down to hand limit

### Combat Explained

Combat is straightforward but has hidden depth:

- Declare an attack targeting an enemy champion or ally
- Your opponent can **block** with one of their allies
- Both sides deal damage equal to their **Power**
- The defending unit is destroyed if damage meets or exceeds its health

---

## Building Your First Deck

A standard Grand Archive deck contains:

| Component | Count |
|-----------|-------|
| Champion card | 1 |
| Main deck cards | 50 |
| Level cards | Up to 3 per level |

### The Golden Rule: Know Your Champion

Every deck is built **around your champion's strengths**. Before adding any card, ask:

> *"Does this card support what my champion wants to do?"*

For example, if your champion rewards you for playing many cheap actions, you want lots of low-cost cards. If your champion rewards big attacks, you want high-power cards with good pitch value.

### Pitch Curve

One of the most important deckbuilding concepts is your **pitch curve** — the distribution of memory values across your deck. You want:

- Enough 1-cost cards to have plays every turn
- Enough 2-3 cost cards for your mid-game power turns
- A few expensive finishers for when you're ahead

---

## Champion Spotlight: Lorraine

**Lorraine, Wandering Warrior** is one of the most popular beginner champions for good reason:

- Her ability is easy to understand but rewards good play
- She has strong defensive tools
- Her card pool is well-supported

Here's a simplified example of how her turn might look:

```
1. Set two cards as memory (generate 2 memory)
2. Play a 2-cost attack action → deals 4 damage
3. Use Lorraine's ability → draw 1 card
4. Attack with Lorraine → deals 3 damage
```

In a single turn, you've dealt **7 damage**, drawn a card, and set up your next turn.

---

## Floating Memory

When you play a card and don't spend all your memory, the leftover floats to your next turn. This is called **Floating Memory** and it's one of Grand Archive's most strategic elements.

**Example:**
- You have 3 memory available
- You play a 2-cost card
- 1 memory **floats** to your next turn
- Next turn you start with 1 memory + however much you generate

Learning to float memory efficiently separates good players from great ones.

---

## Common Beginner Mistakes

### ❌ Pitching your best cards too early

When you need memory, it's tempting to pitch your strongest cards. Don't — pitch cards with effects you can live without in that moment.

### ❌ Over-committing to the board

Playing every ally you draw feels good, but it leaves you vulnerable. Keep cards in hand as a buffer.

### ❌ Ignoring the level-up track

Levelling up your champion is almost always correct the moment you can afford it. The power boost is significant.

### ✅ What to do instead

- Plan your memory generation 2 turns ahead
- Keep at least 2 cards in hand at the end of your turn
- Level up as soon as possible

---

## Where to Play

You can play Grand Archive in several ways:

- **Local game stores (LGS)** — find events at the [Grand Archive website](https://www.grandarchivetcg.com)
- **Tabletop Simulator** — free fan-made mod for online play
- **Proxied play** — print cards to test decks before buying

